The '''Multiple Sclerosis Society of Great Britain and Northern Ireland''' ('''MS Society''') is now an charitable organisation with Charitable Company status. The MSS funds research and support to those affected by MS.  The [http://www.mssociety.org.uk MS Society] are also committed to bringing high quality health and social care within reach of everyone affected by MS, and are currently (2012) involved with the Neurological Alliance, and other charities including [http://www.parkinsons.org.uk Parkinson's UK] and [http://www.mndassociation.org/ MND] (Motor Neurone Disease) in campaigning against changes to the Welfare System in the UK [http://www.dwp.gov.uk/policy/welfare-reform/].

Founded in 1953 by Richard Cave, whose wife had MS, the MS Society is the UK's largest charity for people affected by Multiple Sclerosis (MS). It is a membership organisation, with c.38,000 members (2012), made up of PAMS (People Affected by MS).

The MSS prides itself on its network of branches (over 300) and 9000 volunteers, who help to raise awareness and funds for the Society, both locally and nationally.

MS Society activities include:
* funding MS research into cure, cause and quality of life. [http://www2.mssociety.org.uk/research/funded_research/major_investments/myelin_repair_centre/index.html Cambridge Myelin Repair Centre]. Since 1956, the MS Society has invested over £136 million of today’s money in research.
* providing grants (financial assistance) to individuals
* education and training on MS to those affected directly and to health professionals
* producing numerous publications on MS:  [http://www.mssociety.org.uk/publications/ Publications downloads]
* running a freephone specialist Helpline (0808 800 8000)
* providing local support groups through a branch and region network
* organising events such as [http://www.mssociety.org.uk/ms-events/ms-life-2012 MS Life] and Living with MS, both designed to be educational and social events.

The MS Society receives most of its income from personal donations. It also raises money through sponsored events. 

The charity has a Research Strategy Committee chaired by Brian Meaden. The MS Society recognises the need for systematic reviews of existing pre-clinical research as well as clinical research, about which the charity [[SABRE Research UK]] raises awareness.

